[2] Azerbaijan - Deaths take global total over 100
Date: Tue 14 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters News Agency, Tue 14 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://today.reuters.com/news/newsArticle.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2006-03-
14T151650Z_01_N12232814_RTRUKOC_0_US-BIRDFLU.xml&archived=False>

Azerbaijan Deaths Take Global Bird Flu Deaths Beyond 100
--------------------------------------------------------
Avian flu was thought to have claimed another 3 lives in Azerbaijan,
taking the death toll from the virus beyond 100.
The Azeri victims, who died earlier this month [March 2006], fell ill
after contact with sick birds and were not thought to have infected
each other, local health officials said. Azerbaijan, which lies on a
crossroads between Asia and Europe, reported its 1st bird flu deaths
overnight, citing results from tests at a mobile laboratory borrowed
from a U.S. naval facility in Cairo. The World Health Organization
(WHO) said it believed the tests were reliable, adding it awaited
results from a British laboratory before confirming [that] the H5N1 virus
was to blame.
Local officials said they believed the Azeri victims contracted the virus from
sick birds. "The (deceased) fell ill as a result of contact with birds," said
Shyakar Babayeva, head nurse at the Lung Disease Research Institute in the
capital, Baku, where they were treated. "I do not believe the virus passed
from human to human," she told Reuters.
Azerbaijan is located on the Caspian Sea, sandwiched between Russia
and Iran. It also shares a border with Turkey, where 4 children died
from bird flu in January 2006. The 3 victims were from a village in
the Salyan region, in the south of the country near the Caspian Sea
coast.
Details were sketchy, but local media said 2 of them were teenagers,
a girl of 17 and a boy aged 16. It was not clear whether all 3
victims came from the same family.
[Byline: Rufat Abbasov, Lada Yevgrashina & Stephanie Nebehay]
